# Git commit authorship

## Why GitHub shows "Cursor"

Cursor can append a trailer to the commit message:

`Co-authored-by: Cursor <cursoragent@cursor.com>`

GitHub then lists Cursor as a co-author. The **author** line may still be
correct; the trailer is what you want gone.

## Rules for agents

- Do **not** add any `Co-authored-by:` line for Cursor or `cursoragent@cursor.com`.
- Do **not** pass flags or environment variables whose purpose is to inject
  that trailer.
- Use the human's existing `git config user.name` and `user.email` (repo
  `include.path` / local config is fine). Do not switch the commit author to a
  Cursor identity.

## Automated fix in this repo

`.husky/prepare-commit-msg` removes `Co-authored-by: Cursor` lines from the
message file before the commit is recorded. You should still avoid adding the
trailer upstream of the hook.

## If a commit already has the trailer (before push)

```bash
f=$(mktemp)
git log -1 --format=%B | grep -v '^Co-authored-by: Cursor' > "$f"
git commit --amend -F "$f"
rm -f "$f"
```

Then push. **pact-web `master` may forbid force-push**; if the bad commit is
already on `master`, an org admin must temporarily allow force-with-lease, or
you accept the trailer on that SHA until a policy exception is granted.

## Other PACT repos

`pact-auth`, `pact-notify`, and `.github-private` use the same no-trailer rule;
they do not ship the Husky hook, so rely on amend before push when needed.
